## 5. State Management with Zustand

### Store Design

One store per domain. Keep stores thin — they hold state and simple actions, not business logic.

```tsx
// stores/use-project-store.ts
import { create } from "zustand";
import { immer } from "zustand/middleware/immer";

interface ProjectState {
  projects: Project[];
  activeProjectId: string | null;
  isLoading: boolean;
}

interface ProjectActions {
  setProjects: (projects: Project[]) => void;
  setActiveProject: (id: string | null) => void;
  addProject: (project: Project) => void;
  removeProject: (id: string) => void;
}

export const useProjectStore = create<ProjectState & ProjectActions>()(
  immer((set) => ({
    projects: [],
    activeProjectId: null,
    isLoading: false,

    setProjects: (projects) => set((s) => { s.projects = projects }),
    setActiveProject: (id) => set((s) => { s.activeProjectId = id }),
    addProject: (project) => set((s) => { s.projects.push(project) }),
    removeProject: (id) => set((s) => {
      s.projects = s.projects.filter((p) => p.id !== id);
    }),
  }))
);
```

### Rules

- **Use selectors.** Never `const store = useProjectStore()`. Always `const projects = useProjectStore((s) => s.projects)` to avoid unnecessary re-renders.
- **No API calls inside stores.** Stores are state containers. Data fetching happens in hooks or server components.
- **Use `immer` middleware** for stores with nested state updates.
- **Ephemeral UI state stays in React.** Modal open/close, hover states, local form inputs — use `useState`. Zustand is for shared cross-component state.
- **Derive, don’t store.** If a value can be computed from existing state, compute it with a selector, don’t store it separately.

```tsx
// ✅ Derived state via selector
const activeProject = useProjectStore(
  (s) => s.projects.find((p) => p.id === s.activeProjectId) ?? null
);
```

