## 9. Code Quality & Patterns

### Clean Code — With Reason

Apply clean code principles where they improve clarity and maintainability. Don’t blindly follow rules.

- **Name things by what they represent, not what they are.** `useProjectPermissions` not `useData2`.
- **Functions do one thing.** If describing a function requires “and,” split it.
- **Early returns over deep nesting.**

```tsx
// ✅ 
if (!user) return <AuthPrompt />;
if (!project) return <NotFound />;
return <ProjectDashboard project={project} />;

// ❌
if (user) {
  if (project) {
    return <ProjectDashboard project={project} />;
  } else {
    return <NotFound />;
  }
} else {
  return <AuthPrompt />;
}
```

- **Extract magic values.** No `if (role === "admin")`. Use `const ROLES = { ADMIN: "admin" } as const`.
- **Comments explain *why*, not *what*.** The code says what. Comments say why it’s not obvious.

### SOLID (Adapted for React)

|Principle                    |In React                                                                           |
|-----------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
|**S** — Single Responsibility|Each component has one reason to change. A `UserAvatar` doesn’t fetch user data.   |
|**O** — Open/Closed          |Extend via composition (`children`, slots), not by modifying source.               |
|**L** — Liskov Substitution  |A `shared/Button` works anywhere a `ui/Button` works. Don’t break the contract.    |
|**I** — Interface Segregation|Don’t force components to accept props they don’t use. Split large prop interfaces.|
|**D** — Dependency Inversion |Components depend on abstractions (hooks, contexts), not concrete implementations. |

### DRY — But Don’t Over-Abstract

- **Rule of Three.** Duplicate code is tolerated twice. On the third occurrence, extract.
- **Wrong abstraction is worse than duplication.** If two components share 60% logic but differ in intent, keep them separate and extract only the truly shared pieces (hooks, utilities).

